---
description: When to split a package into a browser-safe index.client.ts vs a single index.ts
alwaysApply: true
---

# Browser-safe entry split is opt-in, not the default

Do **not** add an `index.client.ts` (browser-safe barrel) / `exports`
map split to a package by default. A single `index.ts` is the norm.

Only introduce the `index.client.ts` + `index.ts` split (the
`@dbx-tools/shared` shape) when the package genuinely has a server-only
surface that **cannot** run in the browser - i.e. something that imports
`node:*`, pulls in a Node-only subtree (e.g. `@databricks/appkit`'s
typegen / native bits), or otherwise breaks a client bundle. In that
case, keep the browser-safe exports in `index.client.ts` and let
`index.ts` re-export it plus the server-only namespaces.

If everything in the package is browser-safe (pure types, sync helpers,
isomorphic runtime), keep one `index.ts`. Don't create
`index.client.ts`, a `browser` condition, or `*.browser.ts` variants
speculatively.

## Scaffolding

- Every `bun run create` kind - standard, `--plugin`, and `--shared` -
  produces a **single `index.ts`**. None of them emit `index.client.ts`
  or an `exports` split.
- `--shared` just seeds a dependency-free, browser-safe contract package
  (`index.ts` re-exporting `src/protocol.ts`), like
  `@dbx-tools/appkit-mastra-shared`.
- If a package later grows a server-only (`node:*`) surface, add the
  `index.client.ts` + `exports` split by hand (mirror
  `@dbx-tools/shared`). Don't split pre-emptively.
